12.11.24  1:29 am   Can you please use this formula based off of "working hard or hardly working"?

(-Ing Verb) (adjective) or hardly (same -ing verb)

      i notice that the magic of this phrase hinges upon 'hard' and 'hardly' being opposites in this context, despite having the same root. your formula didn't take this into account. it would have been hard to find another such pair of similar words with opposite meanings, but you didn't request that, NOR did you rule out simply just using 'hard/hardly' again. the more i look at this, the more it seems to appear that you didn't really think this through. but anyway, the clear sensible answer here i believe is 'thinkin hard or hardly thinkin'

12.10.24  9:18 am   Any tips for learning a new language?

      the way i approach a brand new language is this: find some videos of people having real conversations (not scripted) like podcasts or something like that. the more you enjoy the content, the better. but you also need it to have a reliable human-made transcript. then get the transcript translated. then just start getting curious about which sounds mean what, and go from there. listening is king, but the transcript will unlock what you're hearing. a crucial important tip is do NOT expect yourself to 'remember' or 'memorize' anything. that's just not how it works. with more and more and more and more and more exposure, whilst being curious, the brain will do what it does naturally, which is learn. your brain is much better at learning than you will ever understand. trust that this will happen naturally with enough exposure and curiosity. the only other thing that may throw you off is how ridiclulously long it takes
